excerpt: The world's largest koala sanctuary, with a zoo housing Australian native animal species.
detail_description: Lone Pine Koala Sanctuary, located just north of Brisbane's CBD, is the world's largest koala sanctuary and a haven for Australian native wildlife. Visitors can watch koalas lounging in gumtrees, hand-feed kangaroos, and observe endangered species like the cassowary. The sanctuary offers keeper talks throughout the day and opportunities to learn about various Aussie wildlife while exploring at your own pace.
name: Lone Pine Koala Sanctuary
address: 708 Jesmond Rd, Fig Tree Pocket QLD 4069, Australia

excerpt: Tucked away in City Hall, this museum offers historical city exhibits, artwork & a clock tower tour.
detail_description: Nestled within Brisbane's City Hall, the Museum of Brisbane (MoB) is a free-to-visit art gallery and museum that showcases the city's history, culture, and contemporary art. Visitors can explore historical exhibits, including artifacts like convict leg irons and a 200-year-old telescope once owned by Sir Thomas Brisbane. The museum also offers free tours of the iconic City Hall clock tower.
name: Museum of Brisbane
address: Level 3, Brisbane City Hall, 64 Adelaide St, Brisbane City QLD 4000, Australia

detail_description: South Bank is a vibrant and bustling area in London, located along the southern bank of the River Thames. It's known for its lively atmosphere, with an array of cultural attractions, entertainment venues, and dining options. Visitors can enjoy stunning views of the city skyline and take leisurely strolls along the riverfront promenade. South Bank is also home to iconic landmarks such as the London Eye, Shakespeare's Globe Theatre, and the Tate Modern art gallery.
name: South Bank
address: South Brisbane QLD, Australia

excerpt: Contemporary art from Australia, Asia & the Pacific exhibited in a modern riverside building.
detail_description: The Gallery of Modern Art (GOMA) is a contemporary art museum located in a modern riverside building in Brisbane, Australia. Established in 2006 as an extension of the Queensland Art Gallery, GOMA has quickly gained recognition as one of the largest modern and contemporary art galleries in Australia.
name: Gallery of Modern Art
address: Stanley Pl, South Brisbane QLD 4101, Australia

excerpt: Landmark botanical garden offering an array of plant life, ponds, picnic areas & a concert venue.
detail_description: Nestled in the heart of Brisbane, the City Botanic Gardens is a captivating botanical haven that offers a diverse range of plant life, tranquil ponds, and inviting picnic areas. This verdant oasis serves as a living museum of botanical collections and provides an idyllic escape from the urban hustle and bustle. Visitors can explore manicured lawns, riverside pathways shaded by majestic fig trees, and charming ponds inhabited by ducks.
name: City Botanic Gardens
address: 147 Alice St, Brisbane City QLD 4000, Australia

excerpt: Expansive, acclaimed park featuring contemporary display gardens, waterways & an amphitheater.
detail_description: Roma Street Parkland is a renowned and expansive park in Brisbane, offering contemporary display gardens, waterways, and an amphitheater. It's a horticultural gem and a welcoming community space with spectacular flower gardens, children's playgrounds, accessible facilities, lakes, cafes, and event hosting. Located in the heart of the city next to Roma Street train station, it provides a delightful haven for relaxation, picnics by the lake, wildlife spotting, and exploring newly refurbished playgrounds.
name: Roma Street Parkland
address: 1 Parkland Blvd, Brisbane City QLD 4000, Australia

excerpt: Lively venue at a former container wharf featuring stalls with international street eats & beer.
detail_description: Eat Street Northshore is a vibrant venue located at a former container wharf in Brisbane. It was created by four well-known personalities and features 80 colorful shipping containers offering a variety of international street food, cocktails, arts and crafts, and clothing. The market comes alive on Friday and Saturday nights with fairy lights illuminating alleyways filled with global cuisine, pop-up bars, and live music. Visitors can indulge in Japanese pizza, local seafood, wood-fired pizza, Korean fusion burgers, and more.
name: Eat Street Northshore
address: 221D MacArthur Ave, Hamilton QLD 4007, Australia

excerpt: Busy pedestrian strip lined with hundreds of shops, from department stores to fashion boutiques.
detail_description: Queen Street Mall is a bustling pedestrian strip in the heart of Brisbane's Central Business District, attracting over 25 million visitors annually. It features a diverse range of shops, from department stores to trendy boutiques, spread across renowned arcades like Wintergarden and Brisbane Arcade. Additionally, the nearby Eat Street Markets at Hamilton's North Shore offer an array of street food, cocktails, arts and crafts within colorful shipping containers.
name: Queen Street Mall
address: Queen St, Brisbane City QLD 4000, Australia

excerpt: Cool, repurposed tram power station featuring plays, concerts & other shows, plus a speaker series.
detail_description: Brisbane Powerhouse, a former coal-fired power station transformed into a lively arts center, offers a diverse range of entertainment including plays, concerts, and speaker series. The venue hosts cutting-edge photographic installations, music performances, and indie band sessions on Sunday afternoons. Originally constructed in 1927 and repurposed from a decommissioned power station, it now serves as an arts and cultural hub featuring performing arts, visual arts, festivals, and free community events.
name: Brisbane Powerhouse
address: Yuggera and Turrbal Country, 119 Lamington St, New Farm QLD 4005, Australia

excerpt: Large, multi-venue destination with a performing arts centre, several museums & the State Library.
detail_description: The Queensland Cultural Centre, situated in the heart of Brisbane, is a vibrant and diverse destination that offers a range of cultural experiences. Visitors can explore multiple venues including a performing arts centre, various museums, and the State Library. The precinct boasts premier museum and gallery spaces such as the Queensland Museum with its dinosaur exhibits, hands-on science displays; QAGOMA featuring world-class art and interactive kids' areas; and the State Library of Queensland offering daily sessions for children.
name: Queensland Cultural Centre
address: South Brisbane QLD 4101, Australia

excerpt: Pedestrian- & bicycle-friendly bridge offering picturesque views of the city skyline & river.
detail_description: The Story Bridge in Brisbane is a pedestrian- and bicycle-friendly bridge that offers stunning views of the city skyline and river. It is one of the city's most distinctive landmarks, adding character to the urban landscape. While not as famous as Sydney's Harbour Bridge, it provides an equally impressive vantage point for taking in scenic views of the city.
name: Story Bridge
address: State Route 15, New Farm QLD 4169, Australia

excerpt: Enclosed gondolas carry visitors 200 feet into the air day & night for panoramic views of Brisbane.
detail_description: The Wheel of Brisbane is a must-visit iconic landmark offering breathtaking 360-degree panoramic views of the city. Rising 60 meters above the ground, visitors can enjoy enclosed gondolas that provide safety and comfort for up to 8 people. Whether it's during the day, at sunset, or at night, each ride includes an engaging audio tour of Brisbane's landscape.
name: The Wheel of Brisbane
address: Russell St, South Brisbane QLD 4101, Australia

excerpt: Scenic mountaintop viewpoint with expansive city views, plus a cafe & restaurant.
detail_description: Mount Coot-Tha Summit Lookout offers breathtaking panoramic views of the city and its surroundings. It is a popular spot to watch the sunset, with vibrant colors painting the sky as twilight approaches. The lookout is located near Brisbane Botanic Gardens Mount Coot-tha, a 138-acre subtropical conservatory featuring diverse native and exotic plants, including the largest collection of Australian rainforest trees in the world.
name: Mount Coot-Tha Summit Lookout
address: 1012 Sir Samuel Griffith Dr, Mount Coot-Tha QLD 4066, Australia

excerpt: Planetarium in the Mount Coot-tha Botanic Gardens with educational shows, exhibits & an observatory.
detail_description: Located within the Mount Coot-tha Botanic Gardens, the Sir Thomas Brisbane Planetarium is a hidden gem in Brisbane. Opened in 1978, it features the Cosmic Skydome, which offers educational shows about the solar system and tours of the night sky. The planetarium also houses an observatory, Galaxy Gift Shop, and Sundial Courtyard.
name: Sir Thomas Brisbane Planetarium
address: Mount Coot-Tha Rd, Mount Coot-Tha QLD 4066, Australia

excerpt: Mount Coot-tha is a mountain and a suburb of the City of Brisbane, Queensland, Australia. Visible from much of the city, Mount Coot-tha is a popular bushland tourist destination including the Mount ... Wikipedia.
detail_description: Mount Coot-Tha, located in Brisbane, Queensland, Australia, is a prominent mountain and suburb offering stunning views of the city. It is a popular tourist destination known for its bushland and natural beauty. The area surrounding Mount Coot-Tha includes several other suburbs and provides visitors with opportunities for outdoor activities and exploration.
name: Mount Coot-Tha
address: Queensland 4066, Australia

excerpt: Busy, modern waterside development with restaurants, breweries & a sleek, contemporary hotel.
detail_description: Howard Smith Wharves (HSW) is a bustling waterfront development in Brisbane, offering a variety of dining and entertainment options. Situated along the river with stunning views of the Story Bridge and city skyline, it's an ideal spot for hanging out with friends. The precinct features a range of restaurants and bars, including Felons Brewing Co., La Mexicana, Greca, and more.
name: Howard Smith Wharves
address: 5 Boundary St, Brisbane City QLD 4000, Australia

excerpt: Fortitude Valley is packed with nightlife, offering everything from dive bars and mellow live music venues to rooftop cocktail lounges and pumping dance clubs. Relaxed brunch cafes mix with cosy Chinatown eateries and upmarket European restaurants. Indie record stores and art galleries add a bohemian vibe, while the Judith Wright Centre showcases performing arts from contemporary dance to poetry recitals.
detail_description: Fortitude Valley is a vibrant neighborhood known for its lively nightlife scene. From dive bars to rooftop cocktail lounges and dance clubs, there's something for everyone. The area also offers a diverse dining experience, with brunch cafes, Chinatown eateries, and upscale European restaurants. Visitors can explore indie record stores, art galleries, and the Judith Wright Centre for performing arts.
name: Fortitude Valley
address: Queensland, Australia

excerpt: 56-hectare, subtropical botanic gardens featuring native & exotic plants, plus workshops & events.
detail_description: Nestled at the base of Brisbane's tallest mountain, Mt. Coot-Tha, Brisbane Botanic Gardens Mt Coot-tha spans over 56 hectares and is renowned as Queensland's premier subtropical botanic gardens. The gardens boast a diverse collection of native and exotic plants, including the largest assortment of Australian rainforest trees globally. Visitors can explore various themed spaces such as the Japanese Garden, Lagoon and Bamboo Grove, Fern House, and Fragrant Plants and Herb Garden.
name: Brisbane Botanic Gardens Mt Coot-tha
address: 152 Mount Coot-Tha Rd, Mount Coot-Tha QLD 4066, Australia

excerpt: Sprawling public park featuring grassy expanses, recreational facilities & an arts centre.
detail_description: New Farm Park is a sprawling public park located along the Brisbane River, offering expansive grassy areas, a beautiful rose garden, and various recreational facilities. Visitors can enjoy stunning sunset views and take a leisurely stroll on the New Farm Riverwalk, which connects the park to Howard Smith Wharves. The park provides ample space for picnics among trees and roses, as well as playgrounds and free Wi-Fi.
name: New Farm Park
address: 1042 Brunswick St, New Farm QLD 4005, Australia

excerpt:
Kangaroo Point is an inner southern suburb in the City of Brisbane, Queensland, Australia. In the 2021 census, Kangaroo Point had a population of 9,689 people.
The suburb features two prominent attractions, the Story Bridge and Kangaroo Point Cliffs. Wikipedia.
detail_description: Kangaroo Point is a charming suburb located in the City of Brisbane, Queensland, Australia. With a population of over 8,000 people, it offers a mix of urban living and natural beauty. The area is home to iconic landmarks such as the Story Bridge and the stunning Kangaroo Point Cliffs. It's surrounded by other vibrant neighborhoods like Highgate Hill, New Farm, and West End.
name: Kangaroo Point
address: Queensland, Australia

excerpt: Panoramic group walks in safety harnesses across the top of Brisbane's iconic cantilever bridge.
detail_description: Experience the thrill of walking across Brisbane's iconic Story Bridge with the Story Bridge Adventure Climb. This exhilarating activity offers panoramic views of the city and Brisbane River, making it a must-do for adventure seekers. In addition to the bridge walk, participants have the option to abseil 30 meters down one of the pylons for an added adrenaline rush.
name: Story Bridge Adventure Climb
address: 5 Boundary St, Brisbane City QLD 4000, Australia

excerpt: 52,500-capacity stadium hosting rugby and soccer home games for Brisbane teams, plus major concerts.
detail_description: Suncorp Stadium, formerly known as Lang Park, is a top-notch venue in Brisbane with a seating capacity of 52,500. It serves as the home ground for rugby and soccer teams in the city and also hosts major concerts featuring renowned artists like Ed Sheeran and Taylor Swift. The stadium's events calendar is always packed with exciting games and performances. Whether you're a sports enthusiast or a music lover, Suncorp Stadium has something for everyone.
name: Suncorp Stadium
address: 40 Castlemaine St, Milton QLD 4064, Australia

excerpt: Small, palm-fringed inner-city swimming beach along a lagoon with a picnic area & snack stall.
detail_description: Streets Beach is a man-made inner-city swimming beach located in South Bank, Brisbane. It offers a picturesque lagoon with palm-fringed sandy shores and clear blue waters, providing an amazing view of the city and the river. This popular tourist spot is also frequented by locals who enjoy its convenient location and easy access via public transport.
name: Streets Beach
address: Stanley St Plaza, South Brisbane QLD 4101, Australia

excerpt: Museum featuring science, culture & natural history exhibits specific to the Queensland region.
detail_description: The Queensland Museum Kurilpa in Brisbane is a fascinating destination that offers a deep dive into the history, science, and natural wonders of the Queensland region. From prehistoric exhibits to modern-day displays, this museum provides an enriching experience for visitors of all ages. As the flagship campus for the Queensland Museum, it houses a diverse collection of artifacts, animals, and fossils that showcase the region's rich heritage.
name: Queensland Museum Kurilpa
address: Corner of Grey and, Melbourne St, South Brisbane QLD 4101, Australia

excerpt: Active historic government building with guided tours featuring the clock tower, plus a museum.
detail_description: Brisbane City Hall is a historic government building with a neoclassical facade that dates back to the early 20th century. The architecture combines elements from the Pantheon in Rome and the campanile belltower in Venice, making it a unique sight to behold. Visitors can take guided tours of the clock tower and explore the Museum of Brisbane on the third floor, which showcases local history from the city's founding to its present cosmopolitan status.
name: Brisbane City Hall
address: 64 Adelaide St, Brisbane City QLD 4000, Australia

excerpt: New Farm is a leafy residential neighbourhood that draws families to its namesake park, with riverside BBQ spots, grassy fields and jungle gyms. The Riverwalk links to the city centre via waterfront pedestrian and bike paths. Brisbane Powerhouse shows contemporary plays and concerts in a graffitied red-brick industrial building, while the area's relaxed dining scene has cheery brunch cafes and kid-friendly eateries.
detail_description: New Farm is a charming residential area known for its lush surroundings and family-friendly attractions. The neighborhood's eponymous park is a major draw, offering riverside BBQ spots, expansive green spaces, and playgrounds for children. The Riverwalk provides convenient access to the city center through scenic waterfront paths for pedestrians and cyclists. Additionally, visitors can enjoy cultural performances at the Brisbane Powerhouse, housed in a distinctive red-brick industrial building adorned with graffiti.
name: New Farm
address: Queensland, Australia

detail_description: South Bank Parklands in Brisbane is a family-friendly water park with pools suitable for all swimming abilities. It features a lagoon and a sandy beach, complete with lifeguards on duty. The park also offers various water features such as a mini Brisbane River, tipping bucket, and surprise squirting fountains. Additionally, visitors can enjoy a playground, numerous cafes and restaurants, and a scenic boardwalk leading to West End or Kangaroo Point cliffs.
name: Snag Fest South Bank
address: Clem Jones Promenade, South Brisbane QLD 4101, Australia

excerpt: West End is a laid-back residential area popular for weekend markets like Davies Park, packed with vendors selling crafts and produce, and Boundary Street, known for its food stalls. Organic cafes and family-friendly Greek and Vietnamese restaurants have a casual vibe, while green spaces with playgrounds like Musgrave Park add to the community feel. Brewpubs and live music venues keep the area happening after dark.
detail_description: West End is a relaxed residential neighborhood known for its vibrant weekend markets, such as Davies Park and Boundary Street. The area offers a variety of organic cafes, family-friendly eateries serving Greek and Vietnamese cuisine, and green spaces like Musgrave Park with playgrounds. In the evenings, West End comes alive with brewpubs and live music venues. This community-focused area provides a casual atmosphere for locals and visitors alike to enjoy food, entertainment, and outdoor spaces.
name: West End
address: Queensland, Australia

excerpt: Elegant, riverside restaurant with a relaxed dining terrace, serving Modern Australian cuisine.
detail_description: Customs House is an iconic riverside restaurant located in Brisbane, Australia. It is housed within a heritage-listed building and offers a unique dining experience with modern Australian cuisine. The restaurant, known as Patina, emphasizes fresh seasonal produce and local seafood in its contemporary paddock-to-plate fare. The menu features elevated dishes such as wagyu beef tartare and 12-hour lamb shoulder.
name: Customs House
address: 399 Queen St, Brisbane City QLD 4000, Australia

excerpt: Scenic 18-hole course with a driving range & pro shop, plus a bistro with a seasonal menu & patio.
detail_description: Victoria Park is a golf lover's paradise, featuring an expansive 18-hole course, a driving range, and even a mini-golf course. The undulating greens are open to all without the need for membership. Visitors can enjoy a round of golf for varying rates depending on the day of the week. Additionally, the park offers a family-friendly bistro with a seasonal menu and an alfresco setting perfect for enjoying views of the lush parkland and city skyline.
name: Victoria Park Driving Range
address: 309 Herston Rd, Herston QLD 4006, Australia

detail_description: Located at the base of Kangaroo Point Cliffs in Brisbane, Queensland, Riverlife Adventure Centre offers a range of outdoor activities and event services. The venue provides a picturesque setting for weddings and bridal photography, with options for ceremonies in the parklands or on the river bank, followed by receptions in a marquee.
name: Riverlife Adventure Centre
address: Naval Stores Kangaroo Point Cliffs Drive, Kangaroo Point QLD 4169, Australia

excerpt: A notorious 19th-century prison, closed in 2002, now offering tours led by former guards & inmates.
detail_description: Boggo Road Gaol, once a notorious 19th-century prison known for its harsh conditions and infamous inmates, is now a captivating heritage site in Queensland. The gaol offers tours led by former guards and inmates, providing an insightful look into Australia's penal history. With stories of notorious prisoners like Slim Halliday and Patrick Kenniff, the gaol's walls are filled with secrets and intrigue. Visitors can even opt for the Boggo Road Ghost Tour for an extra thrill.
name: Boggo Road Gaol
address: 21 Boggo Rd, Dutton Park QLD 4102, Australia

excerpt: 5-level library with floor-to-ceiling windows for river views, plus a writing centre, cafe & Wi-Fi.
detail_description: The State Library of Queensland is a five-level library offering stunning river views through its floor-to-ceiling windows. Located on the riverbank between the Queensland Art Gallery and the Gallery of Modern Art, it's a must-visit for culture enthusiasts and families exploring the precinct. Housing collections like the John Oxley Library and State Reference Library, as well as temporary exhibition spaces, this green building also features a writing center, cafe with Wi-Fi, and The Corner - an indoor play space for kids.
name: State Library of Queensland
address: Cultural Precinct, Stanley Pl, South Brisbane QLD 4101, Australia

excerpt: Long-running brewery featuring guided tours, plus a cool alehouse with craft selections & bar bites.
detail_description: Discover the iconic XXXX Ale House & Brewery in Brisbane, Australia, offering guided tours that delve into the 140+ year history of this legendary brewery. Learn about the brewing process, ingredients, and even how to pour the perfect XXXX beer. Explore the Packaging Hall and witness how these famous beers are labeled and packaged before hitting shelves across the country. After your tour, unwind at the alehouse with a selection of craft beers and delectable bar bites.
name: XXXX Ale House & Brewery Tours
address: 20 Paten St, Milton QLD 4064, Australia

excerpt: Riverside park offering rock climbing, BBQ areas, public art & views of Brisbane's skyline.
detail_description: Kangaroo Point Cliffs Park, also known as River Terrace Park, is a picturesque riverside park in Brisbane offering a range of activities. Visitors can enjoy rock climbing on natural rock walls with stunning views of the city skyline. The park is an ideal spot for capturing beautiful sunsets behind the city, providing vibrant colors and silhouettes against the backdrop of Brisbane's Central Business District.
name: Kangaroo Point Cliffs Park (River Terrace Park)
address: 29 River Terrace, Kangaroo Point QLD 4169, Australia

excerpt: Waterside complex with several climb-aboard historic vessels plus photographs, artefacts & models.
detail_description: Located in a waterside complex, the Queensland Maritime Museum offers visitors the chance to explore historic vessels and view photographs, artifacts, and models. One of its main attractions is the river class frigate HMAS Diamantina, which was built in Maryborough and launched in 1944. Visitors can tour the warship's engine room, crew rooms, galleys, showers, engineers' rooms, and surgeons' rooms.
name: Queensland Maritime Museum
address: 412 Stanley St, South Brisbane QLD 4101, Australia

detail_description: Shorncliffe Pier is a historic timber pier in Brisbane, Australia, offering stunning views and a picturesque setting. It stretches 350m into Bramble Bay and is known as the city's largest timber pier and one of the longest recreational piers in the country. The pier has undergone restoration and rebuilding, making it perfect for activities such as picnics, photography, fishing, or leisurely strolls.
name: Shorncliffe Pier
address: Park Parade, Shorncliffe QLD 4017, Australia

excerpt: Featuring a Nepalese pagoda, this heritage site is the last global exhibit from the '88 World Expo.
detail_description: The Nepalese pagoda, a heritage site from the '88 World Expo, is a beautiful example of Nepalese architecture, standing tall in the midst of a tropical rainforest grove. It's an ideal place to relax and connect with nature, and is a perfect way to start your day in Brisbane.
name: Nepalese Peace Pagoda
address: Clem Jones Promenade, South Brisbane QLD 4101, Australia

excerpt: Zoned 138-acre botanic gardens with native displays, a tropical dome, kids' trail & bonsai house.
detail_description: Nestled in Brisbane's Mt Coot-tha, the Mount Coot-tha Botanic Gardens span 138 acres and offer a unique tropical ambiance. Unlike typical botanic gardens, this site showcases diverse floral displays within the city's heart. With over 52 hectares of plant life, it provides ample exploration opportunities for adults and children alike. The gardens feature wildlife sightings and duck feeding activities, making it an ideal destination for animal enthusiasts.
name: Mount Coot-tha Botanic Gardens
address: 152 Mount Coot-Tha Rd, Mount Coot-Tha QLD 4066, Australia

detail_description: Spirits of the Red Sand offers an immersive Indigenous storytelling experience, located just a 30-minute drive from the CBD. Visitors are treated to a traditional Welcome to Country ceremony during the day, followed by captivating performances featuring traditional song and dance. The evening culminates in a three-course dinner featuring unique Australian fare such as crocodile, kangaroo, and emu. Guests often have the opportunity to meet and greet with the cast and crew after the show.
name: Spirits of the Red Sand
address: Beenleigh Historical Village, 205 Main St, Beenleigh QLD 4207, Australia
types: Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander organisation

detail_description: Vertigo offers a unique and thrilling dining experience in Brisbane. Guests can enjoy a delicious three-course meal while taking in breathtaking views of the city and witnessing stunning sunsets. The staff is attentive and supportive, ensuring a safe and enjoyable experience for all guests, including adventurous activities like descending from the building. While the food is described as above average, the overall concept is well-executed, providing an exhilarating yet secure experience.
name: Vertigo
address: Yuggera and Turrbal Country, 119 Lamington St, New Farm QLD 4005, Australia

excerpt: This former cement quarry with industrial artifacts offers a water play area & biking/walking paths.
detail_description: Rocks Riverside Park, located in the south-west of Brisbane, was once an industrial estate filled with warehouses but has now been transformed into a sprawling district park perfect for families. The park features a water play area with rock pools, fountains, and shade sails to keep kids entertained and protected from the sun. It offers various activities for kids of all ages including playgrounds, sandpits, and toddler-specific play equipment.
name: Rocks Riverside Park
address: 531 Seventeen Mile Rocks Rd, Seventeen Mile Rocks QLD 4073, Australia

excerpt: Striking brutalist concrete venue for big-name theatre and music, plus ballet and comedy.
detail_description: Nestled in the vibrant South Bank cultural precinct, the Queensland Performing Arts Centre (QPAC) stands as a striking example of brutalist architecture, hosting an array of performances from theatre and music to ballet and comedy. This iconic venue is part of a rich tapestry of cultural institutions along Grey Street, including renowned galleries and museums that draw visitors from near and far.
name: Queensland Performing Arts Centre
address: Cultural Precinct Cnr Grey, Melbourne St, South Brisbane QLD 4101, Australia

excerpt: The Anglican church, a cultural heritage site, features Gothic Revival architecture & wood carvings.
detail_description: St John's Cathedral in Brisbane, Australia is a must-see cultural heritage site with its Gothic Revival architecture and intricate wood carvings. This Anglican church, listed on the Queensland Heritage Register, boasts a unique stone vaulted ceiling, making it the only building of its kind in the southern hemisphere. Designed by architect John Loughborough Pearson and constructed over a century in stages, this cathedral was finally completed in 2009.
name: St John's Cathedral
address: 373 Ann St, Brisbane City QLD 4000, Australia

excerpt: The oldest surviving home in the area, this 1846 house offers a museum with historical collections.
detail_description: Newstead House, located in Brisbane, Queensland, is the oldest surviving residence in the area, dating back to 1846. Initially a colonial Georgian cottage for Patrick Leslie, it has evolved over the years and now serves as a museum showcasing historical collections. The house overlooks the Brisbane River from a lush park and offers visitors a glimpse into Brisbane's history with its late Victorian period style interior.
name: Newstead House
address: Newstead Park Cnr Breakfast Creek Rd &, Newstead Ave, QLD 4006, Australia

detail_description: The MacArthur Museum Brisbane, located in the historic MacArthur Chambers building, offers a unique perspective on Brisbane's history and hosts various special events and educational programs throughout the year. The museum focuses on General Douglas MacArthur's role during World War II and sheds light on Brisbane's involvement in the war effort. With three main exhibits highlighting different aspects of the war, visitors can gain insight into this lesser-known part of Australia's history.
name: MacArthur Museum Brisbane
address: Macarthur Chambers, Level 8/201 Edward St, Brisbane City QLD 4000, Australia

excerpt: City landmark stadium hosting the home matches of the Brisbane Lions cricket team and other events.
detail_description: The Gabba is a renowned landmark stadium in Brisbane, hosting the home matches of the Brisbane Lions cricket team and various events. As part of the city's transformation for the 2032 Brisbane Olympics, The Gabba is set to undergo redevelopment. Additionally, it hosts 'Pets at the Gabba,' a monthly not-for-profit event featuring pet treats and accessories alongside live entertainment and food stalls.
name: The Gabba
address: Vulture St, Woolloongabba QLD 4102, Australia

excerpt: Bustling, Saturday farmers' market providing local fruits & veggies, artisanal goods & food vendors.
detail_description: The Jan Powers Farmers Markets Powerhouse is a vibrant and bustling Saturday market located in various locations across Brisbane, including New Farm Park. The market offers a wide variety of local fruits, vegetables, artisanal goods, and food vendors. With over 300 growers participating, visitors can find an array of fresh farm produce, flowers, breads, meats, fish, plants, organics, spices and more.
name: Jan Powers Farmers Markets Powerhouse
address: The Brisbane Powerhouse, 119 Lamington St, New Farm QLD 4005, Australia

detail_description: Brisbane is a city that seamlessly combines urban living with a strong emphasis on water-based activities. During the annual whale watching season from June to November, Brisbane offers the perfect opportunity to witness the majestic Humpback and Southern Right whales in the calm waters of Moreton Bay. Brisbane Whale Watching provides an unforgettable experience, allowing visitors to observe these magnificent creatures in their natural habitat.
name: Brisbane Whale Watching
address: Shop 5/137 Redcliffe Parade, Redcliffe QLD 4020, Australia

detail_description: Nestled within the vibrant Queensland Museum in South Bank, SparkLab is a treasure trove of interactive experiences designed to ignite curiosity in children aged 6 to 13. This engaging science center features an array of hands-on exhibits that delve into the realms of science, technology, engineering, and mathematics (STEM). Families can explore fascinating topics together through various activities that encourage learning and discovery.
name: SparkLab
address: Grey Street &, Melbourne St, South Brisbane QLD 4101, Australia
